segments.text: that then we interrogated him and then after that by by a policy of the American government we called in a chopper because we were sitting out in the middle of nowhere we called in a chopper and sent him back for higher up interrogation and that's where actually physically they more did the interrogation back there to higher headquarters and found out that he was more that that's what he was he was a he was sent in to infiltrate

get dimensions of the camp so that when he left there that later on if we got hit at night and stuff like this that they would have had all the dimensions so they would know how to shoot their mortars in and hit our bunkers and things like this which would have really been real bad for us.
While you were there, did any of your good friends lose their lives?
Yes, in the same camp we had this guy, a medic.

We have, normally in the Mike Force, when they go out in Ranger outfits, when they went out when we were in Spaceship Forces, there was usually only two Americans go out, and they were out on a search with the Mike Force, and they got ambushed, and he was killed with a .50 caliber machine gun bullets.
He tried to rush it to save everybody else.
It was a real bad fall fright, and he just got up and tried to
rushed a machine gun and he didn't make it.
How did y'all react to such events?
Were y'all getting used to losing friends?
Well, he was closer to most of the Special Forces guy because we had our own people there.
I physically knew the guy and as all death and stuff you feel it's the same way even if he's being killed when you're out in combat and you see them being killed.
It is no different, really.
Somebody being shot or killed is the same, even though he was a Vietnamese or the Americans.
You feel bad, but...
If you look at it in a war, that's some of the things it's just a risk you take when you're in a fight.
So when you witnessed such things, you never questioned the American government reason for being there?
For example, when you lost your friends or the people you knew, did you ever say, is this all worth it?
I really never thought we were there or the American people was not, even because we were there, sent there,

to support the people so I had no aggravation against if a friend of mine got killed or things like this it just yes I felt bad but uh this was part of his job as a military he accepted that responsibility when he joined the army and that's the reason why he he was trying to save lives I guess when he got killed and these were things that you do under those type of situations and uh death is death and uh
It's bad, but you have to learn to accept it when you're in those type of situations and seeing people killed around you.
Fortunately, I never seen as much of it as these guys did because I always stayed in the camps because all we did was build a special camp because we were just engineers, combat engineers.
We only fought as combat engineers or fight as infantry upon being attacked.
and things like this.
Yes, I've seen people killed, and I've seen people brought in killed.
Who do you blame for America's, as you have said that you don't believe that America lost in Vietnam, who do you blame for America's pulling out of Vietnam?
I think the public, the non-military people, your mothers, your fathers, different things like this.
And I think there was a lot of your governors and senators and different things like this from different states and stuff like this that did not support Vietnam, which they talked against it.
They didn't want to see the American troops there and things.
So once it became enough of them
could push it through, then they actually forced us to come out of Vietnam, I think, politically because of the senators, governors, mothers and fathers.
The people just did not want us there no longer because we were not accomplishing anything.
And I think the American people, even the American forces, looked at it that way, too, because our hands were tied in a lot of situations.

You could not cross the Hanoi or go across the Cambodian border or something like this or things like this when that was where they were always heading back to when you were chasing them or doing things like this or fighting them.
So do you think it was alright for Richard Nixon to invade Cambodia?
Do you think that was a proper action?
We had gone and invaded a neutral country.
We were just expanding the war I think then because if we kept expanding it there we were just going to prolong the war.
So...
And plus that was still spreading, like I was saying before, I think, during the talk, that the war is still going on over there in Cambodia because of the refugees and stuff like this.
There are other communists that we're trying to infiltrate in certain areas of Cambodia, and there's just a minute of resistance, real resistance against the forces that are there.
We support it a little bit, but we don't support it as much as we do down in Honduras right now.
in Nicaragua or something like that.
We're supporting the Contras a lot more in fighting down there than we are in Cambodia.
We probably support those people, but not as an all-out public thing.
Do you see a similarity between Nicaragua and Vietnam?
A lot of people say that Nicaragua will be...
There's a possibility, yes.
There could be a possibility that right now we've had American troops lose their lives down there.
Already there's been some American people shot in helicopters and things like this in their support.
Those are how Vietnam started.
Like I was saying at the first of the talk, that when we entered Vietnam, we had advisories there.
What we have in Nicaragua and things right now are advisories.
We also have engineer units down there building roads and different things like this.
It's silhouatic.
This is the way Vietnam started.
And it all depends on really the government, what they want to do about supporting those people, of sending American forces in that area.
If they do, then it could end up being the same thing as Vietnam.
So if you were an advisor to President George Bush, would you advise him against getting involved in Nicaragua or supporting the Contras?
If I was looking at it on a military aspect, and having to go back into combat and fight for a country of that nature, that if our country's President Bush, as the Commander-in-Chief of the U.S.
Forces, and he fully believed

that if we sent American forces down there, that later on in the years, because of us being there, that people would be free and not under a dictator or communist leadership, which would be part of our duty as one of the high forces

NATO or anything of the government to support our comrades in arms if it was became necessary but it would only be the decision of probably the president and the public because I think the public's going to be more involved in this type of war because I think the people are looking at it if we do send troops there it's going to end up being like another Vietnam and they're they're not wanting that so they're they're really holding off and not wanting to do it
I think.

So we're not, it's gonna, we're gonna send advisories, we're gonna support them, and probably stay out of it as much as we can unless it, unless Russia or Cuba or, it really becomes bigger than what it is right now before we probably send troops down there, I think.
If somebody would probably, Russia would end up sending troops there.
or something like that, then we might be more involved of getting involved like we did in Cuba.
When Russia put missiles in Cuba, we got involved.
What role do you think did media have in Vietnam?
Do you think that Walter Cronkite had questioned America's involvement?
They were saying that, how can we save a country by destroying it?
A lot of media people were saying this.
And a lot of people blame media for losing the war.
They said that they didn't have faith in the American ability to carry on.
And a lot of people got discouraged because

I think this was true, the media played a big part in getting us out of Vietnam because of what they published in their media and sending it back here to the Americans that lived in the United States or back here, that this did not sit well with the Americans.
That's the reason why more so the public, because of the press, that we ended up being pulled out of Vietnam because the press, well the press helped.
and, or the media.
So do you think it was right for them to help?
It's not that I don't think they helped.

I think they just was doing, feeling they were doing their job just as well as we were doing our job as government, being sent there from the government as a fighting force to support the Vietnamese government.
They were there doing a job, and they felt that's what they do.
So I guess...
What do you think are the lessons that United States can learn from Vietnam?
How can we avoid another Vietnam?
Are there any words of wisdom you can say?
Not really.
I guess the only thing would be just like to say if I...
It all depends on how well they want to let the American forces after...
They sent us there to let the American people with the American military do their job.

I think that if you let the generals in the military do their job instead of being political about it, like they said when MacArthur, because MacArthur got fired, because MacArthur was wanting to go in and go all through Korea.
China.

and probably if Truman would not have stood in his way and he would have gave to MacArthur's thing, our world might have been a little bit different in Korea or different things like this because we were already at war.
If you're going to accomplish something, I guess you could be like Genghis Khan, just keep going.
And it might have changed the world, but you never know.
We could still be maybe even fighting the war yet.
So you think American people should just place their faith in the hands of their commander-in-chief and the army?
That's why we elected him there in the forces or into the government.

if you don't like what he's doing in four years you just re-elect somebody else that you think but he could be the same way he could still be putting you or our american forces in anything it all depends it all depends on what really i think goes on in the government and since we're going down here at the low thing and only listen to the media that they know more than what the media does sometimes because they've got our intelligence and things like this that

that there could be really a need, and if they say, okay, we've got to send forces to that area to accomplish a mission to keep the people free there, then that would be the decision of the government, which for the president to do it, he still has to have the Senate approve it and things like this.
So it's hard for him to do things like that right now, I think, because of the political situation we had in Nam.
What do you believe should be the course of our foreign policy?
For example, do you believe that it is the duty of America to fight communism in the world?
Or do you think we should try to live side by side with the communist countries?
I think we're learning to accept and live with the communist countries as we're going, just like Nixon, or not Nixon, but Bush and Gorbachev
are negotiating about nuclear missiles and things like this.
It's not that we're living side by side, but we're negotiating for both our futures because of the nuclear weapons that we're supposed to be disarming.
And these are supposed to be monitored real closely to make sure that Russia is doing it.
And a lot of times, we may do something, but Russia don't do it if you don't watch them.
So these type of things will probably, through the government, will just have to be closely monitored
to live side by side with them.
We're accepting them now.
People, when they talk about communism, do they really know what communism is?
It's a word to them.
The only way I think they really would know communism would be go to Russia and live as a Russian under their dictatorship of communism.
It'd be the same as the Russians coming here.
They like to come here

and live because we have a lot of communism living in our country right now because they want they like the American freedom but they still for their own government and their own keeping their own instead of becoming American citizens they still are Russians or whatever nationality that they are here under communism are still claiming that they're communism but they're living in America
If that's the case, why not for them to go back to Russia and let the people explain to them why am I living in America to get away from communism?
To me, it's all he's doing.
He's getting away from communism even though in his own mind he's away from communism.
He's only supporting his government or his country in his mind, but living a good life here in America because everybody likes to come to America, even the Vietnamese and...

Even I think in any war that we fought, the American people, when you were in France and Poland, any place where we were at, the American GIs, the Polish and the French and everything, the women and the kids and everybody wanted to come to America.
They loved to come to America because it was a land of plenty.
And the Russia comes here and lives
He's not under communism as long as he's living here.
We just know that he's here because he is transferred from government to government or he's got diplomatic immunity or whatever.
And he just lives here.
To me, we're living beside communism.
It's just that we're accepting it.
Harry Truman had once said that it must be the policy of the United States to resist communism and stop communism and help any free people who are trying to resist communism.
And one of the reasons our government said we went into Vietnam was that Truman doctrine that we were trying to help free people.
I think that's the reason why we got involved in Vietnam War.
I think if we get involved in Honduras or any other...

type of war or communism type situation where we're in his theory of why we should fight communism that would be the reason that there that we would get involved because that is one of our American as you were saying in Truman's doctrine that he would like to support the American people would demolish communism if they could
and support anybody that asked our help to keep becoming communism.
So do you think we should still follow that principle?
I think we should.

I don't think, if we're going to keep our freedom of speech and everything like this, because if you take probably communism, I think some of your freedom of speech and doing things that we do now would be...

uh... dominated we would not have our bill of rights if we probably come under uh... communism where we where if we come under communism i think the bill of rights and our freedom of speech and different things like this might be a little more hindrance and your way of life would be a little bit more hindrance in some ways for what they do in in probably communism way of doctrine it's probably fairly good because everybody's equal to
Same.
The government gives them everything, and it's divided the country.
It's supposed to be divided to eagerly be entered, but the government's still got control.
Where the American people, as we do at the Bill of Rights, we have the freedom of speech.
If we own something, it is ours.
It's not the government's.
We're in probably a communism country.
Very few people own a lot of stuff.
It belongs to the government or something.
So you believe that the people who want to endorse communism should be left alone, but the people who ask for America's help for freedom should be helped by the United States.

But for example, the Soviet Union, after the Tsarist regime wanted communism, the people in them, and the other countries of Eastern Europe who have endorsed communism, it must not be the policy of the United States to free those countries, right?
If that's what they want, there's nothing for the US government to do about it if the country wants to endorse communism.
If the government does not want to abolish and accept communism, then the United States has nothing to do about going in and stopping the government if the country
wants to become communism, it just becomes communism.
But if they would ask our help to stop communism or something like this, it might be our duty to come in.
It all depends on the situation.
Really, is it that important of us being there to stop communism before we get involved, just like we do in Honduras or Nicaragua?
Right now, I don't think it's worth it to get down and be involved
unless Russia or the Cubans would really come up and put a big force or something in there where they would escalate more of the war down there than what it is right now.

If Russia would actually send big troops like they did in Afghanistan to there, or Cuba and stuff would send a lot of things there and start putting missiles or things like this, this would be a hindrance to us for them to be there because of the situation of them being able to do their...
different things within that area, it'd be a highly military intelligence for them to, especially if they're communists, to find out about what we're doing.
They could put radar or all depends on what they put up, but they could be doing stuff here, which would affect our country.
So if it's going to affect our country, then we do not need it there.
Okay.
Thank you very much, Mr. Paul.
I really appreciate this.
Thank you.
That's okay.
